Registered Veterinary Technicians | Hazel Ridge Veterinary Clinic (916) | Hazel Ave, Fair Oaks, CA COVID Update - Click here to learn more Request Appointment Menu Home About Us Our Team Doctors Registered Veterinary Technicians Client Care Representatives Zsa Zsa Memorial Policies Services Pet Information Senior Pet Resources Contact Us Registered Veterinary Technicians At Hazel Ridge Veterinary Clinic our Registered Veterinary Technicians play an integral role in the care of our clients’ Some of the duties of an RVT include: collecting samples for diagnostic testing, administering medications and fluids, taking radiographs, preparing patients for anesthetic procedures and surgeries, monitoring anesthesia, and overall nursing Our RVTs provide patient treatments and care, much the way human nurses do, which allow our doctors to do more of what they do best: examine and diagnosis potential aliments in your furry family To become an RVT one must successfully complete a veterinary technician program and pass the California State Board Continuing education is required every two years for license Our RVTs have been in veterinary practice for over a combined years (!!) and work as a team to provide the very best care for our Cindy, RVT Cindy brings energy and enthusiasm to any room she She has been an RVT since graduating from Western Career College in In addition, she holds a Bachelor of Science degree from Rutgers University in Animal She has been an RVT at Hazel Ridge since Cindy enjoys coaching new dog owners, especially those with puppies, in how to set up a dog for She has a special interest in exercising pets both physically and mentally as well as behavior She is the proud pet parent of two cats, and her German Shepherd mix named Trina, RVT Trina is our powerhouse she gets the job done! Trina is both very knowledgeable and has excellent technical and nursing She graduated from the Veterinary Technology program at Cosumnes River College in In addition to working at Hazel Ridge, Trina is continuing her education and pursuing a career teaching middle school Her goal is to one day teach children to love science as much as she When not working or studying, Trina enjoys kayaking, walking dogs, cuddling cats, going to the movies, but her favorite pastime is going to Cid, RVT Cid brings her savvy computer skills and love for cats to Hazel Cid began her RVT journey by graduating from the Veterinary Technology program at Cosumnes River College in She left the veterinary field to pursue a career in computer programming, but her love of animals brought her back to veterinary At Hazel Ridge she is able to combine both interests by being our own IT person (lucky for us!). Most of Cid’s remaining time is spent caring for adult cats and kittens with River City Cat Brenna, RVT Brenna first came to Hazel Ridge as a teenager when her family’s dog needed veterinary care in She earned her Bachelor’s degree in Biological Sciences from UC Davis in She worked in the fisheries biology field before attending the Veterinary Technology program at Cosumnes River Brenna came to work at Hazel Ridge as a veterinary assistant in and in became an She works at Hazel Ridge, spending the majority of her time caring for her family and pets: two dogs, two cats, and a desert tortoise named Elise, RVT Elise has personal experience with whelping and raising Her knowledge and experience with both conformation and agility trials compliment her role as an RVT for Hazel Ridge Veterinary She graduated from the Veterinary Technology program at Cosumnes River College in and has been working at Hazel Ridge ever She currently works part time as she is also the busy mother of two young When she is not at Hazel Ridge she is caring for both her human and family including many dogs, cat, goats, and Betsy, RVT Although Betsy is our newest RVT at Hazel Ridge, she is not short on experience! In fact, Betsy began her career in when she graduated from the Veterinary Technology program at Cosumnes River She previously worked at another veterinary clinic until when she joined our Betsy is very knowledgeable, experienced, and comes into any situation with a level head and cool In her free time Betsy enjoys spending time with her six She shares her home with her husband, two dogs, and a Sierra Veterinary Assistant We are happy to have Sierra as part of our team! She is a recent graduate of Mira Loma High School with aspirations of veterinary school in her She started out as all veterinary professionals do with lots of cleaning and learning, but has since branched out assisting the veterinarians with appointments, patient treatments, Sierra is a dedicated, compassionate, and fun member of our When not working or taking community college classes, Sierra enjoys photography, spending time with friends, and being outdoors hiking and She is mom to a young Sheltie and a “In order to keep a true perspective of one’s importance, everyone should have a dog that will worship hi

So we are really happy to announce the official PostgreSQL support in Elephant in the room ✅ Schema drift detection Bytebase will periodically compare the recorded schema with the actual schema and expose the drift if We also provide a view to show the Introduce Anomaly Center Many things can go wrong for your database and unnoticed until an outage We are always thinking of a proactive way to help user catch those Today we introduce Anomaly Center, our attempt to address this A background process will periodically scan potentially anomalies on the managed instances and databases, then expose them in a holistic We currently detect following anomalies and will add more in the future: Database connection issue Backup policy violation Expected backup missing Schema drift Migration schema missing Backward compatible schema migration check (MySQL TiDB) In the last release, we introduce the task check system and introduced the basic SQL syntax In this release, we advance the check to catch backward incompatible schema migration (e.g. RENAME TABLE). What features and benefits will customers pay a premium for? What features and benefits will customers not pay a premium for? Which customers want The lowest cost basic product or service Differentiated premium product or service (See Customer Segmentation) What are customers willing to pay for your product? Many different types of people take part in clinical Some are healthy, while others may have Research procedures with healthy volunteers are designed to develop new knowledge, not to provide direct benefit to those taking Healthy volunteers have always played an important role in Healthy volunteers are needed for several When developing a new technique, such as a blood test or imaging device, healthy volunteers help define the limits of "normal." These volunteers are the baseline against which patient groups are compared and are often matched to patients on factors such as age, gender, or family They receive the same tests, procedures, or drugs the patient group Researchers learn about the disease process by comparing the patient group to the healthy Factors like how much of your time is needed, discomfort you may feel, or risk involved depends on the While some require minimal amounts of time and effort, other studies may require a major commitment of your time and effort and may involve some The research procedure(s) may also carry some The informed consent process for healthy volunteers includes a detailed discussion of the study s procedures and tests and their A patient volunteer has a known health problem and takes part in research to better understand, diagnose, or treat that disease or Research with a patient volunteer helps develop new Depending on the stage of knowledge about the disease or condition, these procedures may or may not benefit the study Patients may volunteer for studies similar to those in which healthy volunteers take These studies involve drugs, devices, or treatments designed to prevent, or treat Although these studies may provide direct benefit to patient volunteers, the main aim is to prove, by scientific means, the effects and limitations of the experimental Therefore, some patient groups may serve as a baseline for comparison by not taking the test drug, or by receiving test doses of the drug large enough only to show that it is present, but not at a level that can treat the Researchers follow clinical trials guidelines when deciding who can participate, in a These guidelines are called Inclusion Exclusion Criteria . Factors that allow you to take part in a clinical trial are called "inclusion " Those that exclude or prevent participation are "exclusion " These criteria are based on factors such as age, gender, the type and stage of a disease, treatment history, and other medical Before joining a clinical trial, you must provide information that allows the research team to determine whether or not you can take part in the study Some research studies seek participants with illnesses or conditions to be studied in the clinical trial, while others need healthy Inclusion and exclusion criteria are not used to reject people Instead, the criteria are used to identify appropriate participants and keep them safe, and to help ensure researchers can find new information they Source: NIH Clinical Research Trials and You | National Institutes of Health (NIH) Benefits of Volunteering for Research Access to Investigational Treatments Active Involvement in Your Health Learning About How New Therapies Get Approved Expanding Medical & Scientific Body of Knowledge Compensation for Your Time We appreciate our We value your We respect Contact Us Stay in touch Questions?
